  "translations": {
    "en": {
      "description": {
        "text": "A newly developed sport crag near Grödinge church. Gullhamra is a large rocky hill with several more or less compact sections of rock on its steep western side. At the southern end is the most continuous, crag-like section. It is over a hundred metres wide, but fairly loose in places. The crag is 15–20 m high. There are currently around fifteen fully bolted sport routes, with several new projects under way. The climbing ranges from easier vertical ground to hard, steep sections and small roofs.",
        "method": "llm",
        "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
        "sourceIds": [
          "legacy:gullhamra"
        ]
      },
      "sections": {
        "allmant": {
          "title": {
            "text": "General",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:gullhamra"
            ]
          },
          "body": {
            "text": "Newly developed sport crag near Grödinge Church. Gullhamra is a large hill with several more or less solid sections of rock on its steep west side. The most extensive, crag-like section lies at the southern end. It is over a hundred metres wide, though parts are fairly loose. The walls are between 15 and 20m high. There are currently around fifteen fully bolted sport routes, with several new projects under way. The climbing ranges from easier vertical ground to hard, steep sections and small roofs.",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:gullhamra"
            ]
          }
        },
        "miljo": {
          "title": {
            "text": "Setting:",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:gullhamra"
            ]
          },
          "body": {
            "text": "The crag has a sunny aspect but is partly shaded by deciduous trees, so it should be climbable from early spring until late autumn. There is a wetland a stone’s throw from the crag. There can be a lot of mosquitoes in summer. Don’t forget insect repellent. There are plenty of wild boar in the area. Take it easy and be careful.",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:gullhamra"
            ]
          }
        },
        "vagbeskrivning": {
          "title": {
            "text": "Directions",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:gullhamra"
            ]
          },
          "body": {
            "text": "From Tumba, follow Dalvägen (road 226) towards Vårsta for about 4km. Drive through Vårsta and turn left onto road 225 towards Nynäshamn. After 1.8km, turn right towards Skanssundet and Grödinge Church. Pass the church after 2.5km. Continue for about 200m to the 70 signs. Just beyond the signs is a small area on the left with parking for no more than two or three cars. Alternatively, there is a large car park at the church.\n\nBus 727 from Tumba station towards Skanssundet stops at Grödinge Church. Journey time about 15min.\n\nThere is a good view of the crag from the road. But if you see it, you have driven too far!!\n\nThe actual approach starts from the parking area.",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:gullhamra"
            ]
          }
        },
        "karaktar": {
          "title": {
            "text": "Character",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:gullhamra"
            ]
          },
          "body": {
            "text": "The crag rises straight from ground level and is fairly high and impressive in places. There are several smaller and larger ledges that have to be climbed past. As a result, some routes feel effectively shorter but also steeper than expected.\n\nThere are plenty of really sharp holds and edges. The rock quality varies and looks fairly poor in places, but is generally somewhat better than it appears. All routes are fully bolted, and a great deal of loose rock and blocks has been removed. It is still not unusual for the odd hold to come off, so a cautious belayer wears a helmet. Leading uncertain/closed projects can be extremely dangerous!",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
